<subSubSection id="FCE76510FFB2D555D0FA2EBB8FFCF9D2" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" type="description">
<paragraph id="B442369BFFB2D555D0FA2EBB8DC7FBE6" blockId="1.[151,1437,868,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis id="8689EA89FFB2D555D0FA2EBB8D2BFC76" bold="true" box="[199,345,903,928]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Description.</emphasis>
The genus is characterised by a remarkable sexual dimorphism (see 
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D4622EBB88B1FC76" box="[1119,1219,903,928]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Figs 1, 3</figureCitation>
): males (
<quantity id="73059B7EFFB2D555D5172EBB8CB6FC12" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.895" metricValueMax="1.93" metricValueMin="1.86" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" unit="mm" value="18.95" valueMax="19.3" valueMin="18.6">18.6–19.3 mm</quantity>
) are larger and more robust than females (
<quantity id="73059B7EFFB2D555D2802E908F1AFC12" box="[701,872,940,965]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6149999999999998" metricValueMax="1.65" metricValueMin="1.58" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" unit="mm" value="16.15" valueMax="16.5" valueMin="15.8">15.8–16.5 mm</quantity>
), having the pronotum longer and more gibbose (especially the callar lobe), longer antennae (especially antennomeres 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D3872EEC8F96FC3E" box="[954,996,976,1000]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
are prolonged; see Measurements and 
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D0AA2EC88C8BFBDA" box="[151,249,1012,1037]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D0F22EC88C8BFBDA" box="[207,249,1012,1036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
</figureCitation>
) and longer legs. In females the pronotum is shorter and weakly gibbose, antennomeres 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D4DE2EC8897FFBDA" box="[1251,1293,1012,1036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
and legs are distinctly shorter (
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D15E292B8DD5FBE6" box="[355,423,1047,1072]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Fig. 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D1AA292B8DD5FBE6" box="[407,423,1047,1072]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B442369BFFB2D555D0FA29008FFCF9D2" blockId="1.[151,1437,868,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Lateral margins of pronotum forming a sharply explanate lamina (see 
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D3C52900882DFB82" box="[1016,1119,1084,1109]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D40F2900882DFB82" box="[1074,1119,1084,1108]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
</figureCitation>
). Disc of scutellum basally depressed, its posterior portion elevated. Procoxae bearing a lateral process with bifurcate apex (
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D4E42963894DFBAE" box="[1241,1343,1119,1144]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D52F295C896DFBAE" box="[1298,1311,1120,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="3.0">3</number>
–4
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D57629638905FBAE" box="[1355,1399,1119,1144]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,155,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1438,155,1461]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 11. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 6 – 7 — procoxae with lateral tuberceles (6 — magnification 25 ×, 7 – 50 ×); 8 – 9 — profemur (two different views, 27 ×); 10 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (25 ×); 11 — detail of setiferous and spiniferous tubercles on mesofemur (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 11), 0.5 mm (Fig. 7), 1 mm (Figs 6, 8 – 9). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251066/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
6– 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D55429638905FBAE" box="[1385,1399,1119,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
) in both sexes, larger in males than in females (in one female the apex is simply pointed rather than bifurcate). Profemora of male incrassate, provided with two rows of setiferous to spiniferous denticles intermixed with a few (
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D0A229F08CBEFB32" box="[159,204,1228,1252]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
) larger teeth, the largest tooth being situated near to apex (
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D35E29F08FB8FB32" box="[867,970,1228,1253]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,155,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1438,155,1461]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 11. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 6 – 7 — procoxae with lateral tuberceles (6 — magnification 25 ×, 7 – 50 ×); 8 – 9 — profemur (two different views, 27 ×); 10 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (25 ×); 11 — detail of setiferous and spiniferous tubercles on mesofemur (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 11), 0.5 mm (Fig. 7), 1 mm (Figs 6, 8 – 9). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251066/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D3A129F08FB8FB32" box="[924,970,1228,1252]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="8.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="8.0">8–9</number>
</figureCitation>
); the rows of denticles are separated by a smooth and only slightly depressed longitudinal furrow; profemora of female slender, not incrassate, but otherwise similar to that of male (cf. 
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D1F928288E22FAFB" box="[452,592,1300,1325]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D1C628288E7BFAFA" box="[507,521,1300,1324]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="1.0">1</number>
and 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D27D28288E22FAFB" box="[576,592,1300,1325]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Protibiae of male ventrally with two longitudinal rows of small denticles, apically thickened with a single larger tooth anteapically; females with less developed denticles and anteapical tooth. Mesofemora of males with two longitudinal rows of small setiferous or spiniferous denticles in apical two thirds and a shallow longitudinal furrow in apical third (
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D36828438FACFA4E" box="[853,990,1407,1432]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,155,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1438,155,1461]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 11. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 6 – 7 — procoxae with lateral tuberceles (6 — magnification 25 ×, 7 – 50 ×); 8 – 9 — profemur (two different views, 27 ×); 10 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (25 ×); 11 — detail of setiferous and spiniferous tubercles on mesofemur (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 11), 0.5 mm (Fig. 7), 1 mm (Figs 6, 8 – 9). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251066/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D3AB28BC8FACFA4E" box="[918,990,1408,1432]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="10.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="10.0">10–11</number>
</figureCitation>
); mesofemora of female, as well as metafemora, meso- and metatibiae of both sexes without denticles and longitudinal furrows. Peritreme of the metathoracic scent gland short, oval, directed posterolaterad (see 
<figureCitation id="2CC62A1EFFB2D555D34028FB8872FA36" box="[893,1024,1479,1504]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1395,195,1899]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[196,1396,195,1900]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Ostiole and peritreme. 12 – 14 — Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 12 — peritreme and surrounding evaporatorium (magnification 75 ×), 13 — detail of peritreme (150 ×), 14 — detail of ostiole (250 ×). 15 – 17 — Iphita limbtata Stål, 1870, male, India: Arunachal Pradesh. 15 — peritreme and surrounding evaporatorium (90 ×), 13 — detail of ostiole (250 ×), 14 — detail of peritreme (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm. (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251067/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number id="023524BCFFB2D555D38828F48872FA36" box="[949,1024,1480,1504]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="13.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="12.0">12–14</number>
</figureCitation>
). For description and illustrations of pygophore and paramere see 
<bibRefCitation id="D06C4B6AFFB2D555D1E228D08FF8F9D2" author="Zamal" box="[479,906,1516,1541]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" refString="Zamal, S. &amp; Chopra, N. P. (1990) Aaxonomic [sic!] studies on Indian Largidae (Hemiptera: Heteroptera). Journal of Research Assam Agricultural University, 11, 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1990">
Zamal &amp; Chopra (
